== Confession patterns ==
Confession is the act of admitting the commission of a sin to a priest, who in turn will forgive the person in the name (in the person) of Christ, give a penance to (partially) make up for the offense, and advise the person on what he or she should do afterwards.{{tone inline|date=September 2019}}

According to a 2009 study by [[Roberto Busa|Fr. Roberto Busa]], a Jesuit scholar, the most common deadly sin confessed by men is lust, and by women, pride.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/7897034.stm|title=Two sexes 'sin in different ways'|work=BBC News|date=18 February 2009|accessdate=24 July 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; It was unclear whether these differences were due to the actual number of transgressions committed by each sex,  or whether differing views on what &quot;counts&quot; or should be confessed caused the observed pattern.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Morning Edition|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=100906920|title=True Confessions: Men And Women Sin Differently|publisher=Npr.org|date=20 February 2009|accessdate=24 July 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== In art ==
=== Dante's ''Purgatorio'' ===
The [[Purgatorio|second book]] of [[Dante Alighieri|Dante's]] epic poem ''[[The Divine Comedy]]'' is structured around the seven deadly sins. The most serious sins, found at the lowest level, are the irrational sins linked to the intelligent aspect, such as pride and envy. Abusing one's passions with wrath or a lack of passion as with sloth also weighs down the soul but not as much as the abuse of one's rational faculty. Finally, abusing one's desires to have one's physical wants met via greed, gluttony, or lust abuses a faculty that humans share with animals. This is still an abuse that weighs down the soul, but it does not weigh it down like other abuses. Thus, the top levels of the Mountain of Purgatory have the top listed sins, while the lowest levels have the more serious sins of wrath, envy, and pride.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|last=Climacus|first=John|title=The Ladder of Divine Ascent, Translation by Colm Luibheid and Norman Russell|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=62–63}}&lt;/ref&gt;

# {{lang|la|luxuria}} / Lust&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
  |last=Godsall-Myers|first=Jean E.|authorlink=|title=Speaking in the medieval world|publisher=Brill|year=2003|location=|page=27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hgw0WSuUZn4C&amp;pg=PA27|doi=|isbn=90-04-12955-3}}
&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
  |last=Katherine Ludwig|first=Jansen|authorlink=|title=The making of the Magdalen: preaching and popular devotion in the later Middle Ages|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2001|location=|page=168|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tAxSQ7O4WogC&amp;pg=PA194|isbn=0-691-08987-6}}
&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
  |last1=Vossler|first1=Karl|last2=Spingarn|first2=Joel Elias|title=Mediæval Culture: The religious, philosophic, and ethico-political background of the &quot;Divine Comedy&quot;|publisher=Constable &amp; company|year=1929|location=University of Michigan|page=246|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=McIRAAAAMAAJ|doi=|isbn=}}
