=== Geoffrey Chaucer's &quot;The Parson's Tale&quot; ===

The last tale of [[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer's]] ''[[The Canterbury Tales|Canterbury Tales]]'', the &quot;[[The Parson's Tale|Parson's Tale]]&quot;, is not a tale but a sermon that the parson gives against the seven deadly sins. This sermon brings together many common ideas and images about the seven deadly sins. This tale and Dante's work both show how the seven deadly sins were used for confessional purposes or as a way to identify, repent of, and find forgiveness for one's sins.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=The Canterbury Tales|url=https://www.cliffsnotes.com/literature/c/the-canterbury-tales/summary-and-analysis/the-parsons-prologue-and-tale|website=CliffsNotes|accessdate=30 June 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Dante's Inferno and Saint Augustine's Confessions|url=https://h2g2.com/entry/A1912169|website=h2g2|accessdate=30 June 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Pieter Bruegel the Elder's Prints of the Seven Deadly Sins ===

The Dutch artist [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]] created a series of prints showing each of the seven deadly sins. Each print features a central, labeled image that represents the sin. Around the figure are images that show the distortions, degenerations, and destructions caused by the sin.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title=Pieter Bruegel the Elder: Prints and Drawings|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|date=1 September 2001|location=New York|isbn=9780300090147|editor-first=Nadine M.|editor-last=Orenstein}}&lt;/ref&gt; Many of these images come from contemporary Dutch aphorisms.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|edition=1st Edition / 1st Printing|title=Graphic Work of Peter Bruegel, the Elder: Reproducing 64 Engravings and a Woodcut After Designs By Peter Bruegel the Elder.|publisher=Dover Publications|date=1 January 1963|first=H. Arthur|last=Klein}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Edmund Spenser's ''The Faerie Queene'' ===

[[Edmund Spenser|Spenser's]] ''[[The Faerie Queene]]'', which was meant to educate young people to embrace virtue and avoid vice, includes a colourful depiction of the House of Pride. Lucifera, the lady of the house, is accompanied by advisers who represent the other seven deadly sins.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}

=== William Langland's ''Piers Plowman'' ===

The seven sins are personified and they give a confession to the personification of Repentance in [[William Langland]]'s ''[[Piers Plowman]]''. Only pride is represented by a woman, the others all represented by male characters.

=== ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' ===

[[Kurt Weill]] and [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s ''[[The Seven Deadly Sins (ballet chanté)|The Seven Deadly Sins]]'' satirized capitalism and its painful abuses as its central character, the victim of a split personality, travels to seven different cities in search of money for her family. In each city she encounters one of the seven deadly sins, but those sins ironically reverse one's expectations. When the character goes to Los Angeles, for example, she is outraged by injustice, but is told that wrath against capitalism is a sin that she must avoid.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}}

=== Paul Cadmus' ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' ===

Between 1945 and 1949, the American painter [[Paul Cadmus]] created a series of vivid, powerful, and gruesome paintings of each of the seven deadly sins.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Paul Cadmus {{!}} The Seven Deadly Sins: Pride|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/486323|website=www.metmuseum.org|accessdate=4 December 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Revalorization==
[[Ferdinand Mount]] maintains that [[late modernity|liquid currentness]], especially through [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloids]], has surprisingly given valor to vices, causing society to regress into that of primitive [[Paganism|pagans]]: &quot;covetousness has been rebranded as [[retail therapy]], sloth is [[Downtime (break)|downtime]], lust is [[Sexual exploration|exploring your sexuality]], anger is opening up your feelings, vanity is looking good because you're worth it and gluttony is the religion of [[foodie]]s&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;F. Mount, ''Full Circle'' (2010) p. 302&lt;/ref&gt;

